The section [“Hoisting”](https://github.com/airbnb/javascript/blob/520b6d6/README.md#hoisting) does a good job of explaining the ins and outs of hoisting, but states no rule about that.

For example I consider this a bad practice, because it leads to confusion and possible bugs:

``` js
function example() {
  superPower(); // => Flying

  function superPower() {
    console.log('Flying');
  }
}
```

If the array is empty, the "bad" code will return `<ul></ul>` and the "good" code will return `<ul><li></li></ul>`.

Although I would prefer this over the for loop:

```
function inbox(messages) {
  items = messages.map(function(message) {
    return '<li>' + message.message + '</li>';
  });

  return '<ul>' + items.join('') + '</ul>';
```

This block of code:

```
_this.numericStepper = {
      'limit': [0], // no negative numbers
      'wheelStep': 1,
      'arrowStep': 1
    };
```

I get an warning "extra quotes for key".  Not sure why...

In your guide, you recommended to use one var declaration per variable: 

``` javascript
// bad
var items = getItems(),
    goSportsTeam = true,
    dragonball = 'z';

// bad
// (compare to above, and try to spot the mistake)
var items = getItems(),
    goSportsTeam = true;
    dragonball = 'z';

// good
var items = getItems();
var goSportsTeam = true;
var dragonball = 'z';
```

However, IMHO, I think that the first one is the best because it's more concise and also makes better performance. What do you think?
